	abstract = {In this work we find the optimal trading strategy to sell (or buy) a large position K of a given asset S by a fixed time T . In order to do so, we assume that the price process S is modelled as a geometric Wiener process, instead of the arithmetic approach used in the current literature. Furthermore, the impact due to the trade affects geometrically the price process S. The criteria of optimality is Markowitz's mean-variance and the method of ap-proximating the solution is through a multiperiod binomial model. Alternatively, using our model we study the effect of transacting a large position β of a financial derivative with underlying S. We show, for instance, that if a corporation covers a large position on a given asset with vanilla European put options, the price of the underlying will decrease by the trade. In turn, the price of the contract will increase. Finally, using our model, we find statistical evidence that the volume traded of a derivative is correlated to price movements in the underlying.},
